snippet.textDisplay: Guess all you have to do is have a QB who has the presence of mind to duck down so that a blitzing DB coming in at the speed of heat and going for your legs, has no choice but to go helmet to helmet.  Then that same QB, being the prima donna actor he is, rolls around in agony for a while.  Meanwhile, the refs, who have thrown no laundry mind you suddenly get a call from a replay booth official.  Suddenly, it's now a targeting penalty, a first down for Clemson, the QB is on his feet and appears to be suffering no injury whatsoever AND the opposing team's best DB is out of the game.  How's that for a big play?  Should any of us have been too surprised then when later on a Clemson WR catches a ball, takes over 3.5 steps with it firmly secured in BOTH hands, has it stripped and returned for a defensive TD and THAT ONE GETS OVERTURNED.  One Ohio newspaper showed the refs on it's front page with a caption that read "the real winners of the Fiesta Bowl.
